00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:07.920
JOHNNY LEE: Good
morning, everyone.

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:08.420
Hi.

00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:09.520
It's great to be here.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:12.810
My name is Johnny Lee, and
I'm excited to give you

00:00:12.810 --> 00:00:16.750
an update on where we
are with Project Tango.

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:21.040
For those of you who are less
familiar with Project Tango,

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:24.650
one of the core beliefs and
ideas behind this project

00:00:24.650 --> 00:00:28.180
is the fact that, when we place
our mobile phones on a table,

00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:30.360
they don't actually
understand the things that

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:31.280
are around them.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.570
They don't understand
the extents of the table

00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:35.557
or the room that they are in.

00:00:35.557 --> 00:00:37.140
In fact, almost all
of the information

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:39.070
that they provide
us is constrained

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:42.540
to this little
rectangle you see here.

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.100
They don't understand if we're
relaxing at home with family,

00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:49.800
or if we're in our
workspace collaborating

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:52.460
with our coworkers,
or in a large lecture

00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:57.160
hall such as this, all
facing in the same direction,

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:02.060
or having a nice intimate
dinner with friends and family.

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:06.500
And what we do heavily
depends on where we are.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:09.580
How we feel, how we talk,
how we share information

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:13.960
with each other all depend
on this context of where.

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:18.880
And so rather than try to force
our entire lives into this very

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:22.160
small rectangle, what
Project Tango is trying

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:25.560
to strive for is we're
developing the hardware

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:28.500
and software technologies
to help everything

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:32.600
and everyone understand
precisely where they are,

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:33.480
anywhere.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:36.910
Not just where there's good GPS
coverage, good Wi-Fi coverage,

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:40.170
or Bluetooth beacons, but
any building, any space,

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:44.040
anywhere where we can
go, the devices and tools

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:49.340
that we use also share this
understanding of space.

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:53.490
So last year we introduced
our Project Tango Tablet

00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:54.630
Development Kit.

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:56.480
And this was the
first mobile device

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:59.320
with the sensors and
software to start

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:01.280
to work toward this journey.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:05.270
It includes a 4 megapixel
2 micron camera,

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:08.350
integrated motion tracking
camera, and an integrated depth

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:09.090
sensor.

00:02:09.090 --> 00:02:11.880
And all of these sensors
combined with the Project Tango

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.440
software stack allow
devices to understand

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:18.200
the physical movement
of the device, as well

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:21.710
as its surroundings.

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:23.942
If you actually look at
the-- although we announced

00:02:23.942 --> 00:02:26.400
the tablet over a year ago, if
you actually look at the GFX

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:28.590
Bench, which is very
popular graphics

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:33.520
benchmark for mobile devices,
using the Manhattan 3.0 test,

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:37.050
the Project Tango devices still
rank among the highest marks

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:39.350
with regard to
processor performance

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:40.540
of ARM-based devices.

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:46.380
We're also really happy to
share that since we started--

00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:49.090
since last year, we've also
started shipping our dev kits,

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:52.340
and 3,000 units are in the
field in the hands of developers

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:55.010
working on hundreds of apps.

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:58.950
In a partnership with NASA,
we are also able to have two

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:00.950
of our devices,
early prototypes,

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:03.710
shipped up to the International
Space Station atop

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:08.560
a 530,000-pound Antares
rocket from orbital sciences.

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:10.360
This collaboration
and partnership

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:13.990
is allowing NASA researchers
to use the technology in Tango

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:17.080
to one day help robots
potentially autonomously

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:21.020
navigate the space station.

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:24.130
So what happens when you
have devices that actually

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:26.296
have this sensing capability?

00:03:26.296 --> 00:03:27.920
Well there's a few
different categories

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:30.830
that we think are really
interesting, one of which

00:03:30.830 --> 00:03:32.700
is indoor navigation.

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.260
You can imagine
our devices one day

00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:36.476
not just being able to
take you to the front door

00:03:36.476 --> 00:03:37.850
of a building,
but could actually

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:40.135
navigate you all the way
to the door of the room

00:03:40.135 --> 00:03:42.050
that you wanted to get to.

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:44.020
There's a project inside
of Google starting

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:45.990
to use Project Tango
devices to explore

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:49.440
helping the visually-impaired
navigate indoor spaces.

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:52.740
You can also use the tracking
and spatial reasoning

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:55.750
of the device to transform
parts of your home

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:57.080
into a game environment.

00:03:57.080 --> 00:04:00.510
So I can build a castle
in my living room

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:03.980
and build a forest
in my bedroom.

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:05.907
And of course, there's
emerging new areas

00:04:05.907 --> 00:04:07.490
that are all starting
to get exciting,

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:11.520
such as robotics, AR and VR,
which are all potentially

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:15.270
enabled by the 3D-tracking
capabilities in Tango, as well.

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:21.279
So to give you a briefing,
the core technologies

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:23.410
of a Project Tango device
and the software stack

00:04:23.410 --> 00:04:25.550
that goes on top of
it break into three

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:26.690
different categories.

00:04:26.690 --> 00:04:30.090
The first is motion
tracking, the second

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:35.310
is area learning, and
lastly, depth perception.

00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:38.930
So motion tracking is actually
very similar to your computer

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:39.650
mouse.

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:42.200
If you imagine taking your mouse
and putting it on the table,

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:44.560
as you move it around
on the flat surface,

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:47.140
it tells you the
relative position

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:49.700
you are when you
put it on the table.

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:51.440
Project Tango devices
are very similar.

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:53.200
When you first start
your app, it'll

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.600
tell you your relative
motion relative to when

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:56.720
the app started.

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:59.020
But instead of just
being constrained to 2D,

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:00.850
it actually is full 3D.

00:05:00.850 --> 00:05:07.600
You get X, Y, Z, as well as
three degrees of rotation.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:10.240
The second major concept
is area learning.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:12.840
And if you imagine
closing your eyes,

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:15.720
you actually have sort
of a mental memory

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:17.040
of the shape of Moscone.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:19.040
You know roughly where
you are in this building.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:20.580
You know roughly
how big the room

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.520
is, as well as your own
location within this room.

00:05:23.520 --> 00:05:27.430
And it is that memory that
we call area learning.

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:30.270
So when a Project Tango
device enters a space

00:05:30.270 --> 00:05:35.040
that it's previously been in, as
it starts to explore the space,

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:36.840
it will build a map.

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:39.180
And when it recognizes a
landmark it's seen before,

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:42.540
it can localize itself to
the rest of the building.

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:46.470
And that's called area learning.

00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:50.210
The last major concept that
Project Tango devices provide

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:51.550
is depth perception.

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:53.620
So in Project
Tango-compliant devices,

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:55.320
we include a depth
sensor that uses

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:59.870
infrared signals to measure the
distance to points in space.

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:04.630
This allows us to detect the
floor, the walls, and furniture

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:06.180
in the environment,
and potentially

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:12.520
allows your application or game
to respond to the user's space.

