00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:18.320
which is called Mesh Builder.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:21.150
And what it's doing is
actually using the depth sensor

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:25.120
combined with the 3D
tracking to do a real-time 3D

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:28.590
scan of the stage.

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:34.570
So I have this small table
here with this basket.

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:37.080
And you can see, as I
walk around the stage,

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:42.160
it's actually progressively
building this mesh.

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:45.520
And because this is all running
real time inside of Unity,

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:47.420
I can throw balls
on it, and we're

00:16:47.420 --> 00:16:51.280
updating the physics
in real time as well.

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:53.600
So this basket is actually
a little bit too small

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:58.030
for these balls, so let me take
this one away and give myself

00:16:58.030 --> 00:17:01.650
a slightly more generous
basket right there.

00:17:01.650 --> 00:17:03.580
So let me clear
this and rescan it.

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:09.470
And you can see it kind
of has the larger basket.

00:17:09.470 --> 00:17:13.040
It's progressively
building itself in.

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:18.501
Now if I back up, I can
try to play basketball.

00:17:18.501 --> 00:17:19.260
Come on.

00:17:22.329 --> 00:17:23.140
Yeah!

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:23.919
Yeah!

00:17:23.919 --> 00:17:28.140
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:28.140 --> 00:17:30.280
So with a little bit
of additional help

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:34.100
and some procedural
game geometry,

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:38.080
you could actually turn this
table into a plateau or a mesa.

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:41.980
You could actually literally
have someone building

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:43.579
a set of cushions
with their couch,

00:17:43.579 --> 00:17:45.120
and you could turn
that into a castle

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:47.640
and have your characters
actually run around furniture.

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:49.120
When we first got
this working, we

00:17:49.120 --> 00:17:51.999
were like taping up
blankets in our office

00:17:51.999 --> 00:17:53.540
and using them as
ramps for the ball.

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:01.910
Another simple
utility that we've

00:18:01.910 --> 00:18:03.870
been asked for with
the sensors that you

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:07.910
can do-- with the sensors that
we have in a Tango device--

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:11.780
is being able to simply
measure the environment.

00:18:11.780 --> 00:18:14.930
So imagine we are
shopping for a new table,

00:18:14.930 --> 00:18:18.160
or I have a new bed that I
want to move into the space.

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:20.630
We can use the tracking
sens-- we can use the tracking

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:24.030
data, as well as the 3D
sensing data, to give us

00:18:24.030 --> 00:18:26.280
a simple visual tape measure.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:29.500
So for example, if I want to
measure the size of this table,

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:38.040
I simply use this crosshair,
point it at the table-- whoop,

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:39.650
let me try that again.

00:18:42.884 --> 00:18:43.550
Do it down here.

00:18:46.771 --> 00:18:47.271
OK.

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:52.840
So that gives us a rough
measurement of the environment

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:54.180
between those two points.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:57.160
All I had to do was point the
device like it's a cursor,

00:18:57.160 --> 00:19:00.600
and I can see the distance
between these two corners,

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:05.250
and come over here, and
just by pushing this button,

00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:09.090
we get a rough measurement of
the footprint of this table.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:11.000
The other nice
thing about this is

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.430
that you don't have to be
constrained to flat surfaces.

00:19:14.430 --> 00:19:17.910
If I am trying to,
say, park a truck where

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:19.720
I have all my furniture
still inside of it

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:22.420
and I'm trying to figure out
if I can get through this gap,

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:28.000
I can measure from this table--
from this podium to this wall,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:33.008
and it'll give us a measurement
in free space, just like that.

00:19:33.008 --> 00:19:36.816
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:41.630
So there's a variety of
professional applications

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:43.700
you could already
start with imagining

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:46.750
being able to make use of this
technology and capability.

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:54.700
The last demo I want to
show you is from a partner

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:56.100
called [? Invive ?].

00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:57.870
And what they do
is they specialize

00:19:57.870 --> 00:19:59.520
in product visualizations.

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:01.335
They do high-end
apartment complexes,

00:20:01.335 --> 00:20:04.690
they do products such as
cars and refrigerators.

00:20:04.690 --> 00:20:08.210
And so we had been
working with them,

00:20:08.210 --> 00:20:11.750
and they have this
simple car visualizer.

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:13.840
I need to actually
point in this direction

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:17.297
so that we can actually
place a car on the stage.

00:20:17.297 --> 00:20:18.880
Let me actually pick
it up and move it

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:21.320
so it's not touching the table.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:22.150
There we go.

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:26.710
So I can simply walk
around this car.

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:28.220
Because it's such
a-- it's actually

00:20:28.220 --> 00:20:30.180
a full-size metric
car, it actually

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:32.060
doesn't quite fit on the stage.

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:38.600
So I'm going to use the power
of software and shrink the car.

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:40.110
There we go.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:42.020
OK.

00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:44.210
So now it's almost
toy-sized now,

00:20:44.210 --> 00:20:45.460
but I can sort of look around.

00:20:45.460 --> 00:20:50.670
I can look at the wheels,
I can double tap the hood

00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:52.410
and it'll open up the engine.

00:20:52.410 --> 00:20:54.550
I can get up close to
the engine and talk

00:20:54.550 --> 00:20:56.540
about the different
parts inside of it.

00:20:56.540 --> 00:21:00.680
The respirator, the
carburetor, the engine hood.

00:21:00.680 --> 00:21:03.370
Obviously, you can
do customizations

00:21:03.370 --> 00:21:08.090
to the visualizer, such
as making it a nice racing

00:21:08.090 --> 00:21:10.880
red, or a midnight blue.

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:18.080
I think I can also go and
do body upgrades, which

00:21:18.080 --> 00:21:23.420
I'll show different parts of the
car that I can edit and modify.

00:21:23.420 --> 00:21:28.500
So let me just select the
roof and give it an upgrade.

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:31.620
And just for good
measure, let me scale it

00:21:31.620 --> 00:21:37.120
back up to normal size,
which will actually

00:21:37.120 --> 00:21:39.990
allow me to get in the car.

00:21:39.990 --> 00:21:41.720
But there's not quite
enough stage space,

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:44.610
so I'm just going to go
right through the windshield.

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:47.390
But here I can actually
see the in-car dashboard,

00:21:47.390 --> 00:21:49.530
the steering wheel, the seats.

00:21:49.530 --> 00:21:56.120
If I want to, I can adjust
the interior styles, as well,

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:59.110
[INAUDIBLE] colors.

00:21:59.110 --> 00:22:01.005
So this is just
another simple example

00:22:01.005 --> 00:22:02.760
of our Unity integration.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:05.680
And we started improving the
AR quality of performance,

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:07.230
the registration.

00:22:07.230 --> 00:22:09.680
And again, it's important
to realize that this is all

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:10.920
using motion tracking.

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:13.490
There's no pre-existing
map of the stage,

00:22:13.490 --> 00:22:16.760
and we could easily do
this in any environment,

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:20.230
including your home or a
show room or a retail space.

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:28.742
OK, so those are the demos.

00:22:28.742 --> 00:22:32.630
[APPLAUSE]

00:22:33.602 --> 00:22:35.005
Could we go back to the laptop?

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:40.260
A couple other demos
that I unfortunately

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:43.350
can't do on stage, or it's
very difficult to demonstrate,

00:22:43.350 --> 00:22:45.770
is, of course, things like VR.

00:22:45.770 --> 00:22:49.250
VR has obviously made a lot
of news and press recently,

00:22:49.250 --> 00:22:52.410
and the [? sixth-off ?] tracking
and positioning that Project

00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.270
Tango enables is
interesting for VR.

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:59.280
So we started exploring docking
these tablets to your face

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.950
using the Durovis dive helmets.

00:23:01.950 --> 00:23:04.580
Durovis is a
partner that creates

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:07.680
these plastic shells for
different sized mobile devices.

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:10.990
It's obviously not the most
ergonomically-friendly form

00:23:10.990 --> 00:23:12.520
factor.

00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:14.430
And these tablets were
not designed for VR.

00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:15.920
They have high
latency, they don't

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:17.461
have quite the right
rendering stack.

00:23:17.461 --> 00:23:19.490
But from a sensor and
tracking standpoint,

00:23:19.490 --> 00:23:21.850
they seem to be performing
relatively well.

00:23:21.850 --> 00:23:25.020
So if you have time, you can
go out to our sandbox area

00:23:25.020 --> 00:23:28.180
and you could experience
this village scene in VR.

00:23:28.180 --> 00:23:30.070
You can look on
the ground and get

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:32.250
sort of to the ground
level of the people

00:23:32.250 --> 00:23:35.010
and look around the
different bases.

00:23:35.010 --> 00:23:38.860
We also have a prototype
of doing multi-user VRs.

00:23:38.860 --> 00:23:41.670
Because we have fully
self-contained devices,

00:23:41.670 --> 00:23:43.367
having multiple people
in the same space

00:23:43.367 --> 00:23:45.700
is largely a matter of just
getting the Wi-Fi connection

00:23:45.700 --> 00:23:48.896
working and having positions
shared among each other.

00:23:48.896 --> 00:23:51.020
The great thing about this
is that you can actually

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:53.480
put on the helmet and you
can see each other in VR

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:55.160
and have an actual conversation.

00:23:55.160 --> 00:24:01.197
The mouths actually move to
your vocal-- to the sound.

00:24:01.197 --> 00:24:03.030
If you are on the sandbox
area, you probably

00:24:03.030 --> 00:24:04.970
also saw one of this.

00:24:04.970 --> 00:24:07.190
This is a prototype that
we built with Hasbro.

00:24:07.190 --> 00:24:10.300
They have the NERF brand guns.

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:12.530
And what they did is
they built a 3D mount

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:14.642
that goes on the rail
system of the gun,

00:24:14.642 --> 00:24:16.600
and you just put a Project
Tango-enabled device

00:24:16.600 --> 00:24:18.520
and it allows you to
actually run around

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:20.440
the room in a
first-person shooter.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.690
You can turn and shoot the
enemies from left to right,

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:26.740
but you can also move and duck
behind the boxes in the space.

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:28.270
It's a lot of fun
to actually play,

00:24:28.270 --> 00:24:30.250
and so I encourage you
to try this one out.

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:34.760
So we're really excited
and proud to have

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:36.630
a large number of
partners that have helped

00:24:36.630 --> 00:24:40.190
us mature this platform, both
from a software and hardware

00:24:40.190 --> 00:24:41.190
standpoint.

00:24:41.190 --> 00:24:43.410
And we hope to grow this
networking community

00:24:43.410 --> 00:24:45.390
with hopefully some of
you in this audience we

00:24:45.390 --> 00:24:48.190
can add to this list.

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:52.480
So Project Tango devices
we feel enable a new form

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:53.820
of digital playground.

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:57.460
We can put virtual objects in
the same physical space that's

00:24:57.460 --> 00:25:00.330
meaningful to people.

00:25:00.330 --> 00:25:02.620
We can actually
navigate you to the item

00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:04.490
that you're really
interested in a space

00:25:04.490 --> 00:25:07.160
that you've perhaps
never been before.

00:25:07.160 --> 00:25:08.740
We can also help
you make decisions

00:25:08.740 --> 00:25:11.210
about where to go
in play areas where

00:25:11.210 --> 00:25:14.760
GPS may not be good enough.

00:25:14.760 --> 00:25:18.780
We can enable you to not only
create 3D stories that you

00:25:18.780 --> 00:25:20.640
could look around by
turning your head,

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.747
but you can actually
get up and walk through.

00:25:22.747 --> 00:25:24.580
And I think this is an
interesting dimension

00:25:24.580 --> 00:25:26.790
that we're only starting
to-- we're only beginning

00:25:26.790 --> 00:25:30.520
to explore as a community.

00:25:30.520 --> 00:25:31.910
Obviously, we're
all very excited

00:25:31.910 --> 00:25:35.016
about the emergence
and maturity of AR.

00:25:35.016 --> 00:25:37.760
And 3D tracking and
registration is a core component

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:39.800
of making a good
user experience.

00:25:39.800 --> 00:25:42.010
And when you combine
that tracking ability

00:25:42.010 --> 00:25:44.300
with information
about the environment,

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:49.690
you can actually see beyond the
physical limits of your space.

00:25:49.690 --> 00:25:52.514
And we also know about
robotics and drones.

00:25:52.514 --> 00:25:53.930
And I know I've
been an enthusiast

00:25:53.930 --> 00:25:56.505
and bought one of these
myself, but I also crashed it

00:25:56.505 --> 00:25:58.530
in the first 30 minutes.

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:02.720
So onboard mobile 3D positional
tracking and 3D sensing

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:05.750
is important for things
like collision avoidance

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:06.640
and autonomy.

00:26:06.640 --> 00:26:09.810
So we also see the
technology in these devices

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:13.760
being relevant to
this domain, as well.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:18.880
So this is our Project
Tango Development Kit,

00:26:18.880 --> 00:26:22.510
with a high-performance 2
micron, 4 megapixel camera,

00:26:22.510 --> 00:26:26.840
motion tracking camera,
integrated depth sensing,

00:26:26.840 --> 00:26:30.530
the Tegra K1 processor with
128 gigabytes of storage

00:26:30.530 --> 00:26:35.000
and 4 gigabytes of RAM, which
is on par with a lot of laptops.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.940
And before we had to
request that developers

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:39.790
apply on our website
to get one of these.

00:26:39.790 --> 00:26:42.100
So there was a relatively
limited distribution.

00:26:42.100 --> 00:26:43.600
But we're actually
happy to announce

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:46.200
that earlier this week
we opened up purchasing

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:49.690
to anyone in the United States,
with international locations

00:26:49.690 --> 00:26:51.460
coming soon.

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:53.775
We're also happy to say
that we are offering these

00:26:53.775 --> 00:26:57.277
at a reduced price of $512.

00:26:57.277 --> 00:26:58.860
Given the actual
specs of this device,

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:01.360
this is actually a pretty
aggressive price point.

00:27:04.140 --> 00:27:06.870
To celebrate this new
availability of the devices,

00:27:06.870 --> 00:27:10.180
we are also kicking off our
first app development contest.

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:12.870
So this is an effort to seed
app development and seed

00:27:12.870 --> 00:27:15.570
content on our platform.

00:27:15.570 --> 00:27:18.910
There's three categories
to the contest.

00:27:18.910 --> 00:27:20.310
You can choose to
build a utility

00:27:20.310 --> 00:27:23.910
app, such as measurement,
navigation, room scanning,

00:27:23.910 --> 00:27:25.180
or object scanning.

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:29.310
We have a category for
AR and VR use cases.

00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:31.650
And of course, gaming and
entertainment, which I think

00:27:31.650 --> 00:27:34.780
is one of the ones that's very
easy to imagine seeing demos

00:27:34.780 --> 00:27:37.370
in this space.

00:27:37.370 --> 00:27:40.910
We have seed money for each
milestone for each category,

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:43.330
which exponentially increases.

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:48.450
So 16 selected proposals
will get $1,024.

00:27:48.450 --> 00:27:51.510
Four selected working
prototypes after that milestone,

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:54.210
they'll get up to $2,048.

00:27:54.210 --> 00:27:56.310
And then each category
will have one final app

00:27:56.310 --> 00:28:00.220
selected with $4,096.

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:02.590
Once all the final apps
have been submitted,

00:28:02.590 --> 00:28:06.310
we'll have a user-driven
contest-wide grand prize

00:28:06.310 --> 00:28:09.100
of $8,192.

00:28:09.100 --> 00:28:11.310
All told, together this
is a total cash awards

00:28:11.310 --> 00:28:14.060
up to $95,000.

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:18.380
And we hope this won't be
the last contest we run.

00:28:18.380 --> 00:28:21.594
So proposal entries start
today, and for deadline--

00:28:21.594 --> 00:28:23.510
the first deadline that
you should be aware of

00:28:23.510 --> 00:28:27.190
is June 25th, which is a
deadline for proposals.

00:28:27.190 --> 00:28:31.742
The final APK entry will have to
be submitted by September 23rd.

00:28:31.742 --> 00:28:34.200
To find out more information
about how to enter the contest

00:28:34.200 --> 00:28:38.280
and details, please visit our
Project Tango Google+ community

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:39.870
page.

00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:44.330
So $95,000 to help seed the
app development community.

00:28:44.330 --> 00:28:47.074
And we hope this helps bring
up and surface new partners

00:28:47.074 --> 00:28:48.990
that we actually want
to work with more deeply

00:28:48.990 --> 00:28:50.573
and make a stronger
relationship with.

00:28:53.610 --> 00:28:56.560
We are really excited about the
tech inside of Project Tango,

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:01.270
and we hope that one day it
can be as ubiquitous as GPS.

00:29:01.270 --> 00:29:04.490
But we also know
that-- before we

00:29:04.490 --> 00:29:06.700
used to be fine with phones
that didn't have GPS.

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:09.060
We knew how to get
from home to work,

00:29:09.060 --> 00:29:12.200
we knew how to get to our
restaurants just fine.

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:14.200
But now we wouldn't even
consider buying a phone

00:29:14.200 --> 00:29:16.430
without navigation directions.

00:29:16.430 --> 00:29:19.200
And I think-- we believe
that the technology

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:21.220
inside of Project
Tango would enable

00:29:21.220 --> 00:29:23.920
this sort of feeling as well.

00:29:23.920 --> 00:29:28.300
But we also know that, to
become ubiquitous as GPS,

00:29:28.300 --> 00:29:30.742
tablets are necessarily
the best form factor.

00:29:30.742 --> 00:29:33.200
I'll be the first to admit that
a seven inch tablet doesn't

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:34.810
really fit in my pocket.

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:37.600
And we'd love to be able to
have people carry this around

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:39.091
with them all the time.

00:29:39.091 --> 00:29:41.340
And so that's why we're also
excited to announce today

00:29:41.340 --> 00:29:42.089
a new partnership.

00:29:45.756 --> 00:29:47.900
And that's with Qualcomm.

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:50.770
Qualcomm is the largest
